          "body": "The chapter ends not in mystical heights but at the dinner table and the workshop. Paul addresses six roles — wives, husbands, children, fathers, slaves, masters — and reframes each by reference to the Lord. Wives submit *as is fitting in the Lord* (3:18); children obey *for this is well-pleasing to the Lord* (3:20); slaves work *fearing the Lord* (3:22), *as for the Lord rather than for men* (3:23), *knowing that from the Lord you will receive the reward of the inheritance* (3:24), for *it is the Lord Christ whom you serve* (3:24). The density of *kurios* in vv. 22-25 is unparalleled — five uses in four verses. Paul's point: there is no zone of ordinary life that escapes the lordship of Christ. The Christ who is enthroned above (3:1) reigns in the marriage bed, the nursery, and the slave's daily labor."
