        "title": "Raised with Christ — the new orientation upward",
        "range": "3:1-4",
        "excerpt": "Therefore if you have been raised up with Christ, keep seeking the things above, where Christ is, seated at the right hand of God.",
        "body": "Paul opens chapter 3 with *oun* — therefore. The inferential particle reaches back over everything in chapters 1-2: the cosmic supremacy of Christ (1:15-20), the believer's reconciliation through His blood (1:21-22), the warning against the philosophy that takes captive (2:8), the burial-and-raising-with-Christ in baptism (2:12), and the disarming of the powers at the cross (2:15). On the foundation of all that, Paul now builds the chapter's central imperative: *keep seeking the things above*.\n\nThe conditional *if* (ei) is not doubtful — it is the Greek 'first-class condition' assumed true for the sake of argument. *Since you have been raised with Christ* is the more natural English. The verb *sunegeiro* (raised together with) is past tense (aorist), pointing to the believer's already-accomplished union with the risen Christ at conversion. Paul is not asking the Colossians to *achieve* resurrection-life; he is telling them to live consistently with the resurrection-life they already possess.\n\nThe command has two complementary verbs. *Zeteo* (3:1, keep seeking) is present imperative — ongoing, habitual pursuit. *Phroneo* (3:2, set your mind) is the deeper verb — to be mentally oriented toward, to have one's mindset fixed upon. Paul does not command escapism; the things above are not a fantasy realm but the actual location of the enthroned Christ at the right hand of God (echoing Psalm 110:1, the most-quoted OT verse in the NT). To set the mind above is to live with the awareness that the One who reigns over the cosmos is the same One in whom your life is hidden.\n\nVerses 3-4 give the doctrinal warrant. *You have died* (apothnesko, aorist) — the old life's death is finished. *Your life is hidden (krupto, perfect passive) with Christ in God* — present and ongoing concealment, awaiting future disclosure. The chapter's bookended eschatology is set here: the believer's true life is currently *hidden*, but at the parousia — *when Christ, who is our life, is revealed* — believers will be *revealed with Him in glory* (3:4). The Christological identification is striking: Christ is not merely the giver of our life, He IS our life. As John Calvin observed, this is the deepest privilege of union — that what is Christ's becomes truly ours.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Sunegeiro* (raised together with) and *sunzao* (live together with, cf. Romans 6:8) are Paul's compound verbs for union with the risen Christ — the *sun-* prefix is everything. *Ano* (above) is paired with *epi tes ges* (on the earth, 3:2, 5) to establish the chapter's vertical axis. *Krupto* (perfect passive, *kekruptai*) — has been hidden and remains hidden. *Phaneroo* (3:4, twice) — to make visible, to manifest; the resurrection of the body is the public unveiling of what is now true but unseen."
